================================================================================

Looking at Navigation

An SS screen shows data from a single row of a ResultSet and there is a navigation bar
which changes which row is displayed. The nav bar also controls insert/delete/modify.
In this context a screen is a collection of components, not a window; a window could
have several screens. Typically SS works with ResultSets that are
ResultSet.TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE and ResultSet.CONCUR_UPDATABLE; they allow random
access and can be modified.

By default, when the ResultSet is modified, the database is updated and the ResultSet's
query is re-executed. This preserves how things display, consider an "ORDER BY" clause.
The re-execution is handled by DBNav pre/post ops.

Cursor Navigation
-----------------
A screens displays information for the cursor, which is the current row. If two screens
are displaying data from the same row set, they will be displaying the same data since
the ResultSet only has one cursor.

Random Navigation (not currently implemented)
-----------------
Since usually a ResultSet supports random access, there's no reason why the row being
displayed has to be the cursor row. In particluar, two screen for the same ResultSet
could show different rows.

Notes
-----
- The number of rows is the only thing that must be shared.
  The current row can be kept by the navigation bar.
- Non scrollable ResultSet, TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, could be better handled.
  For example Prev/First disabled.


